title: For Sale:  Remington Model 700 Long Range (30-06 sprg)
postcontent: I have a Remington model 700 Long range in 30-06 sprg. for sale.  I bought this rifle new in the spring of 2014.  Since owning the rifle I have had the barrel cut and recrowned (small recess target) to 22" and had a Timney 510 trigger installed (2.5#).  I have shot 180 rounds of Federal Gold Medal Match ammo through it and have the brass and boxes that I will include in the sale.  This gun was shooting an average of about 1.125" before the above work was done and now averages about .92" with the FGMM ammo.  Again that is my average, you could be better or worse.  These tests were done while firing 5, three round groupings.  I have lost my long range shooting property and have no desire to lug around this heavy rifle for deer season so it is for sale.  The rifle is in great shape the only cosmetic issue is some discoloration from where I had my picatinny rail on it (loctite and bluing don't mix).  If that is a concern I can send a pic to show you.  It does not impact performance and would be covered up by any one piece rail.  I have the original box, x-mark trigger, empty brass and a 9-13" swivel bipod that I will include for $700 OBO.  I would like to sell soon so feel free to shoot me a reasonable offer.

title: For Sale:  Springfield Tower 1871 Musket
postcontent: Following the success of the Model 1870, the Governor of New York ordered 15,000 Remington rolling block rifles and bayonets for his state's militia. These model 1871 rifles were very similar to the Model 1870 rifles, but differed in some details. Field experience with the Model 1870 showed that the mechanism jammed too easily in dusty conditions. Users also did not like loading the weapon at full cock. The Model 1871 included a locking bolt in the breech mechanism. The user pulled the hammer to the full cock position, retracted the breech block spur to expose the chamber, and inserted the cartridge. When the breech block closed, the hammer automatically fell to the half cock position, and the weapon could not be fired until the hammer was once again pulled to the full cock position.[6] Over 20,000 Model 1871 rifles were eventually purchased by the state of New York. The U.S. Army did not greet the Remingtons with much enthusiasm. Foreign sales of the weapon were much more successful. Denmark ordered many of the Model 1870 and 1871 rifles. In 1873, Spain ordered 50,000 Model 1871 rifles, which were delivered in 1875. Numerous other countries, such as France, Chile, Argentina, Cuba, Greece, and Puerto Rico also purchased this rifle.This is a Springfield Tower 1871 three ring musket is missing screw in front ring. Everything else looks to be there including rear flip up sights. All original with wood, bore and rifling in good shape.

title: For Sale:  OBO:  SCCY CPX-2 with Alien Gear IWB holster and all factory accessories
postcontent:
For Sale: SCCY CPX-2
Price: $250 OBO
Round Count: Just over 600
Condition: Used. Cosmetic 95% (very slight slide wear from holster), Mechanical 100% (thoroughly broken in and unfailingly reliable)
Action: DAO, approx. 7.5 lbs, full-length reset (similar to DA revolver trigger)
Capacity: 10+1 rds
Accessories: Hard case, second magazine, extra floorplates (one extra finger grip and one extra flat bottom, currently magazines have one of each installed), all original tools/packaging, Alien Gear IWB holster (broken in but not visibly used, my current [old] carry rig) if the price is right.  If you don't want the holster, price is more negotiable!
Location: North of Ashville, south of Commercial Point

Gooooood evening fellow gun nuts! This has been my EDC gun for 16 months now (it replaced my 1911 due to size constraints) but after running a couple of advanced courses with it, I can't employ (nor do I feel like I need, as a safety precaution) the long DAO trigger as well as I can my SA/DA or striker-fired pistols, so it's time for her to go.

If you prefer DAO for safety (pistol has no external safety) or simply like the feel better than SA or striker, you'll love this pistol. It's incredibly reliable (only two FTEs ever, running reloads. None with factory-loaded ammunition), as accurate as anyone could ever ask a compact DAO to be (once you get used to the trigger), and extremely concealable in almost any carry position. She's got around 650 rounds through her (mostly Speer 147gr and Federal 115gr) without any notable hiccups, and has been gently and properly broken in.

The only "complaint" I can speak of is that she IS NOT rated for +p or +p+ ammunition, so if you carry hot 124gr rounds, you might want to look into switching to the 147gr instead.

I will be purchasing another Gen3 Glock 19 (I gave my last one to my wife, who refuses to give it back after shooting it), so if anyone has one they would be interested in trading for I'm open to options. Beyond that, I'm not really interested in trades unless someone has an AR10 they want to trade for even-up. 

I run a training group, so if anyone is interested and would like to test-fire her just let me know, bring your own ammo, and you're welcome to try before you buy!

Thanks for looking!
